This paper deals with distance measures and algorithms for comparing partially resolved trees, which are commonly used in computational biology. The paper uses techniques from computational geometry and graph theory, which are typically found in the computer science sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also discusses parametric distances and Hausdorff distance, which are commonly used in machine learning and statistics, and thus could be classified under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of tree topologies, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorics, and thus could be classified under cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.CG.
